04704nam a22007455i 9780691187778DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911877787 a10.1515/97806911877782doi  a(DE-B1597)501815  a(OCoLC)1076412472  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDS135.U42bL8578 2007eb 7aHIS0100102bisacsh 7aHIS0220002bisacsh 7aHIS0400002bisacsh04a947.7/92231 aStanislawski, Michael, eauthor.12aA Murder in Lemberg :bPolitics, Religion, and Violence in Modern Jewish History /cMichael Stanislawski. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2007  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: The Murder and Its Background -- tChapter One: Galicia and Its Jews, 1772-1848 -- tChapter Two: Lemberg and Its Jews, 1772-1848 -- tChapter Three: A Reform Rabbi in Eastern Europe -- tChapter Four: Rabbi Abraham Kohn in Lemberg, 1843-1848 -- tChapter Five: Revolution and Murder -- tPart Two: The Investigation, Sentence, and Appeal -- tChapter Six: Abraham Ber Pilpel, Murderer? -- tChapter Seven: The Indicted Co-Conspirators -- tChapter Eight: Magdalena Kohn v. the Austrian Empire -- tConclusion -- tAfterword -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex  aHow could a Jew kill a Jew for religious and political reasons? Many people asked this question after an Orthodox Jew assassinated Israeli Prime Minister Itshak Rabin in 1995. But historian Michael Stanislawski couldn't forget it, and he decided to find out everything he could about an obscure and much earlier event that was uncannily similar to Rabin's murder: the 1848 killing--by an Orthodox Jew--of the Reform rabbi of Lemberg (now L'viv, Ukraine). Eventually, Stanislawski concluded that this was the first murder of a Jewish leader by a Jew since antiquity, a prelude to twentieth-century assassinations of Jews by Jews, and a turning point in Jewish history. Based on records unavailable for decades, A Murder in Lemberg is the first book about this fascinating case. On September 6, 1848, Abraham Ber Pilpel entered the kitchen of Rabbi Abraham Kohn and his family and poured arsenic in the soup that was being prepared for their dinner. Within hours, the rabbi and his infant daughter were dead. Was Kohn's murder part of a conservative Jewish backlash to Jewish reform and liberalization in a year of European revolution? Or was he killed simply because he threatened taxes that enriched Lemberg's Orthodox leaders? Vividly recreating the dramatic story of the murder, the trial that followed, and the political and religious fallout of both, Stanislawski tries to answer these questions and others. In the process, he reveals the surprising diversity of Jewish life in mid-nineteenth-century eastern Europe. Far from being uniformly Orthodox, as is often assumed, there was a struggle between Orthodox and Reform Jews that was so intense that it might have led to murder.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aJewsxCultural assimilationzUkrainezLʹvivxHistory. 0aJewszUkrainezLʹvivxHistoryy18th century. 0aJewszUkrainezLʹvivxHistoryy19th century. 0aReform JudaismzUkrainezLʹvivxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187778zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187778.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN